    <!-- FAQ -->
    <section class="content-section">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <div class="methodology">
        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-question">What are the most shorted stocks right now?</div>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            As of March 2026, the most heavily shorted US stocks include <strong>{studyMeta.mostShortedTicker}</strong> at {studyMeta.maxShortPercent}% short interest of float, followed by LCID (42.5%), NTLA (42.0%), MARA (38.6%), and MPW (36.1%). Our <a href="#squeeze-tracker">interactive Squeeze Tracker</a> above ranks all {studyMeta.totalStocksAnalyzed} stocks by short interest and squeeze potential. For a focused list, see our <a href="/most-shorted-stocks-march-2026">most shorted stocks</a> breakdown.
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-question">How do you predict a short squeeze?</div>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            Our proprietary <strong>Squeeze Score</strong> (0-100) combines five factors: Short % of Float (0-30 pts), Days to Cover (0-20 pts), Price Momentum (0-20 pts), Short Interest Change (0-15 pts), and Institutional Support (0-15 pts). Stocks scoring above 60 historically show the highest squeeze probability — they combine high short interest with positive momentum and institutional backing that constrains share supply. No single factor is sufficient; the power is in the combination.
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-question">Do heavily shorted stocks outperform the market?</div>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            Not consistently. While short squeezes can produce dramatic short-term returns (GME in 2021 gained 1,700% in three weeks), the average heavily shorted stock underperforms the S&P 500 over 3-12 month periods. Stocks are usually shorted for fundamental reasons — declining revenue, unsustainable debt, or competitive threats. The edge comes from identifying the <em>exceptions</em>: stocks where the bearish thesis is weakening while short interest remains elevated. That's exactly what our Squeeze Score attempts to quantify.
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-question">What is considered a high short interest percentage?</div>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            The average S&P 500 stock has roughly 2-3% short interest as a percentage of float. Here are the thresholds we use: <strong>Below 5%</strong> — normal range. <strong>5-10%</strong> — elevated, worth monitoring. <strong>10-20%</strong> — high, indicates significant bearish sentiment. <strong>20-30%</strong> — very high, squeeze risk escalates. <strong>Above 30%</strong> — extreme, historically rare and associated with maximum short squeeze potential. In our study, {studyMeta.heavilyShortedCount} of {studyMeta.totalStocksAnalyzed} stocks exceed the 10% threshold.
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-question">How often is short interest data updated?</div>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            FINRA requires brokers to report short positions twice per month — around the 15th and the last business day — with data published roughly 10 days after each settlement date. Our Short Interest Study is updated monthly with fresh data from Yahoo Finance and SEC EDGAR. We recalculate all Squeeze Scores with each update. For real-time short data, institutional traders use services like S3 Partners or Ortex, which estimate intraday short interest from securities lending data.
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

